## Phase 4: Key Findings — Mapped to CVEs and Real-World Context

These are the vulnerabilities both scanners and the Nmap `vuln` scripts should consistently surface on Metasploitable 2. Each is paired with a short real-world reference point — not because these exact instances were ever exploited "in the wild" via this lab, but because the *same flaw class* has caused real incidents.

| Port/Service | Vulnerability | CVE | Real-world reference |
|---|---|---|---|
| 21 — vsftpd 2.3.4 | Backdoored command shell triggered via crafted username | CVE-2011-2523 | In 2011, the official vsftpd-2.3.4 source tarball on the project's download server was replaced with a malicious version containing this backdoor for roughly a month before being caught — a real supply-chain compromise. |
| 6667 — UnrealIRCd 3.2.8.1 | Backdoored daemon allows remote command execution | CVE-2010-2075 | In 2009–2010, the official UnrealIRCd download archive was similarly replaced with a trojanized build that was distributed for months. |
| 139/445 — Samba | "username map script" allows remote command execution | CVE-2007-2447 | This is a different bug class than, but conceptually related to, the 2017 "SambaCry" flaw (CVE-2017-7494) that was used in real cryptocurrency-mining worm campaigns against exposed Samba servers. |
| 3632 — distccd | Misconfigured to accept commands from any host, allowing arbitrary code execution | CVE-2004-2687 | Distcc misconfigurations have historically been a common "easy win" in CTFs and real internet-facing exposure scans (e.g., flagged repeatedly in Shodan-based research on exposed build services). |
| 1099 — Java RMI Registry | Insecure default config allows remote class loading / code execution | CVE-2011-3556 | Java RMI exposure is a recurring finding in real enterprise pentests where internal management interfaces are accidentally reachable. |
| 5900 — VNC | No/weak authentication ("password") | N/A (config issue) | Open VNC servers with blank/default passwords have repeatedly been found exposed on the open internet via mass scans, leading to real unauthorized desktop access incidents. |
| 512–514 — rsh/rlogin | Cleartext, trust-based remote login (`.rhosts`) | N/A (legacy protocol) | r-services were a primary lateral-movement vector in real intrusions through the 1990s–2000s, which is why they're now considered legacy/deprecated in hardened environments. |
| 2049 — NFS | World-exported shares with no host restriction | N/A (config issue) | Misconfigured NFS exports remain a common finding in internal network assessments, often leading to sensitive file disclosure. |
| 8180 — Apache Tomcat | Default/weak manager credentials (`tomcat:tomcat`) | N/A (config issue) | Default credential reuse on management consoles is consistently one of the top initial-access methods cited in annual breach reports (e.g., Verizon DBIR). |

